{
  "texts": [
    "Furthermore, many nations' policies and legal frameworks stress making AI technology open and affordable, reflecting the principle of \"AI technology for all.\"",
    "For example, the European Union has funded initiatives such as \"AI4EU\" to encourage the development of inclusive AI applications and, through its digital policies, has encouraged member states to strengthen AI-related education and training in order to narrow digital divides (European Commission 2019).",
    "Beyond EUwide legislation, individual member states have referred to ensuring that \"no one is left behind\" in their national AI strategies, as exemplified by",
    "\"AI justice for all\" underscores both formal justice and substantive justice.",
    "Formal justice requires that AI not discriminate against specific populations, demanding the prevention of bias and the fair treatment of all users, while substantive justice calls for AI not to exacerbate social inequality but instead to provide equitable opportunities for people of all social classes, races, genders, and economic backgrounds."
  ]
}